---
layout: layouts/base.njk
title: Evaluation-First Delivery — If We Can't Measure It, We Don't Ship It
description: How sysf.io builds evaluation sets from your own documents, runs the base-vs-RAG-vs-fine-tune ablation, gates go-live on agreed metrics, and monitors drift in production.
faq:
  - q: How big does an evaluation set need to be?
    a: Smaller than you'd fear, bigger than a demo. Fifty carefully chosen tasks with gold answers already separate "works" from "impresses"; 150–300 buy per-category breakdowns — document types, languages, edge cases — large enough to act on. We report confidence intervals alongside the scores — on samples this size a two-point difference is noise, and we'd rather tell you that than sell it. Your domain experts spend hours on this, not weeks, and the set becomes a durable asset that outlives any particular model.
  - q: Who defines what "correct" means?
    a: Your experts, in writing, before anything is built. For extraction tasks that's exact-match on fields; for drafting it's a rubric your reviewers apply; for Q&A it's answer accuracy plus citation faithfulness — the answer must be right and grounded in the retrieved source. We refuse vague success criteria because they're how pilots end up "successful" and unused.
  - q: What happens if the system misses the bar?
    a: The report says so, with the failure categories broken out — and the production roadmap explains what would close the gap and what it would cost, or recommends stopping. A fixed-scope Pilot that can end in a documented "no" is precisely what makes its "yes" worth something.
---
